        {
          "title": "Oppenheimer",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Opened to $80M, a huge number for a three-hour biopic, with IMAX 70mm prints sold out across L.A."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "Oppenheimer: The Deep Dive",
      "note": "full spoilers",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Oppenheimer",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "Chris and Sean each saw it twice (once in 70mm, once in IMAX) and preferred the taller IMAX frame even for scenes of men talking in rooms. Verdict: a great movie with real flaws, built out of American Prometheus and Nolan's usual burdened-genius themes, carried by Cillian Murphy and an ensemble (Damon, Blunt, Pugh, Downey Jr., Affleck) doing a lot of the emotional work. The Trinity test around the two-hour mark is the peak; the black-and-white Strauss/Senate hearing hour after it split the room: Chris thought it dragged, Sean and Amanda thought the kangaroo-court framing paid off."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Where it lands in the Nolan rankings",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Dark Knight",
          "year": 2008,
          "note": "Amanda's pick for Nolan's best: structurally close to Oppenheimer, an hour and a half of setup before it turns into, as she put it, driving around with Two-Face for a while."
        },
        {
          "title": "Memento",
          "year": 2000,
          "note": "In Sean and Amanda's Nolan top three: a lean idea for a movie, incredible execution on no budget."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dunkirk",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "Chris's favorite Nolan alongside Inception; barely any dialogue, characters that are, in his words, stand-ins for concepts rather than people."
        },
        {
          "title": "Inception",
          "year": 2010,
          "note": "Chris's other favorite. Came up earlier too, as the sharper version of the dead-wife-as-plot-device problem the group has with how the movie handles Kitty."
        },
        {
          "title": "Tenet",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "Sean still loves it and still doesn't fully understand it."
        },
        {
          "title": "Interstellar",
          "year": 2014,
          "note": "Rewatched over the weekend; the group agrees the sound design and burdened-man-of-science framing are a direct dry run for Oppenheimer."
        },
        {
          "title": "Insomnia",
          "year": 2002,
          "note": "Chris's rewatch pick, the Pacino remake he thinks set the template, even ahead of Memento, for Nolan's men undone by their own competence."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
